  <span id="freeText14849158281552958999" style="display:none">During the years of political upheaval in 1990s Algeria, Hayat, a young second wife to a high-ranking military figure, occupies herself with writing fiction. Childless, bored and restless, she writes romantic fiction that seems to falter. Curious about some of the scenes she's written, she finds that some of the details are real. Her curiosity piqued, she goes to the cinema to see a movie that she included in her novel. There she encounters a man who speaks only a few words, inhales his cologne, and never sees his face. But the figure overtakes her imagination. The interlocking of fiction and reality sets her on a path that eventually leads to a second encounter with the man.<br /><br />This is a novel about love, writing, the interplay between how we view life and how it changes us over time. The narrator uses quotes from other writers to launch into discussions about life and writing, about the state of life and politics in Algeria at this time, and the meaning of love and commitment. Although the author's views of love are seem immature, especially for the time period, her play with the plot is admirable, the fiction braiding with real life and bringing the narrator to a deeper and more mature engagement with life.<br /><br />Well written though not at all florid and overwritten, the story was sometimes tedious in the Hayat's repeated focus on the importance of love and passion, which seemed at times little more than a way to break the boredom of her life.</span>
