  <span id="freeText6152971404542680720" style="display:none"> "A kiss so beautiful you wish you would die"<br />The main character is Hayat a writer in Constantine, Algeria, a beautiful city joined by an amazing topography and beautiful bridges. As a woman of this city she has to be careful about going to films on her own, coffee houses are just for men, seating beside a male in a car makes tongues wag, buying cigarettes is not respectful for a woman; a place where the most innocent of trysts could bring dishonour or worst, in this society she writes about love or she mostly wants to write about love but her country and the men in her life in her books are busy killing being killed, becoming martyrs, thinking of becoming martyrs, taking pictures before a suicide mission that she as a little girl collects in an envelope and forgets till a name brings back the memory of these photos.. <br />She thinks of love of being loved, submitting to love, love as submission, kisses so beautiful you wish you would not survive them. She thinks about this so powerfully she conjures one of her character and loves him the man of flesh not ink, while the world around her sinks in violence, patriotism and religious fervour.<br />This love she wants is naive, youth full in its innocence, unrealistic, sexually immature, prohibited in its development, bound, expanded in allegory and language, a sensuality that is full of barriers, but because of this the passion burns intense and ready to jump and set it all on fire. But most of all is not as she imagines, reality intrudes and expectations are shattered.<br />The character is a prisoner of her culture and a participant of its mistakes, she complains about the violence but believes in hipper nationalism, wants a Pan Arab nation. While her husband a high ranking officer hunts islamist, and journalist, her brother supports terrorism and may also be hunting army officers and journalists, but she can not bring herself to believe he could be violent, she repeatedly expresses that what she fears most is God (this is not a negative fear but a form of submission of respect).<br />A very interesting book, that is strange and beautiful, with some interesting plot twists, a story that wants to be literate and literature, a book that explores feelings as if they were independent of culture and history. The writer mention many poets and writers but gives no real political position on her views of her society, her character as a woman has no real voice or opinions about the politics, at best she reports the social disintegration at worst she is an spectator of her own life. She loves her brother, respects her husband and desires a man, in peril because of this two other characters, she appeases all but confronts none. But she is still fascinating and strong in a world that tries to submit her .<br /></span>
