  <span id="freeText5976277864789769205" style="display:none">I did it! I finished it! My first Arabic book! This is an accomplishment!<br /><br />Bored at Work? Review Time!<br /><br />Well! What can I say? It's true, this book was very difficult for me to read. The last arabic books I read was my literature book in school and that was written in big block letters and was pretty simple. <br />Not only did I find some difficulty in the wording, but the story itself was set in war torn politically riled Algeria, which I have absolutely no clue about. <br /><br />But, that all did not matter, because this book is beautiful. The writing is so poetic and romantic. The story was odd, it was part political, part a love story, part a tribute to journalism and the power of writing, but it worked. Somehow, it worked. It made me laugh, it made me cry, it made me nod my head with agreement. <br /><br />Would I read another story for her? I don't think so. I want to immortalize this lovely story and reading something similar will ruin it's value. <br /><br />Would I recommend this? Yes, I would, but not for everyone. The book is odd, the story isn't logical and it's not meant to be I believe. I'm sure there is a bigger meaning to this book, one that I missed out on but again, it does not matter! <br /><br />I'm happy to have read this and I want to share one paragraph that really stood out for me:<br /><br /><p>لأن القبلة هي الفعل العشقي الوحيد الذي تشترك فيه جميع حواسنا . نحن في حاجة إلي حواسنا الخمس لتقبيل شخص ولكن لسنا في حاجة أليها جميعا لنمارس الجنس . القبلة تفضحنا لأنها حالة عشقيه محض لا علاقة لها بالرغبات الجنسية التي تشترك فيها مع كل الحيوانات . و لذا نحن قد نمارس الحب مع شخص لا نشعر برغبه في تقبله و قد نكتفي بقبلة من أمرأة تمنحنا شفتاها من الحمي ما تعجز أجساد كل النساء على منحنا أياه </p><p></p></span>
